06497nam a22009615i 9789812308818DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20082008si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898123088187 a10.1355/97898123088182doi  a(DE-B1597)492017  a(OCoLC)1041989969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aUA833.5b.H37 2009 7aPOL0370002bisacsh04a327.5922200aHard Choices :bSecurity, Democracy, and Regionalism in Southeast Asia /ced. by Donald K. Emmerson. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (422 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms and Note on References to the ASEAN Charter -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1. Critical Terms -- tAssessments -- t2. Sovereignty Rules -- t3. Institutional Reform -- tIssues -- t4. Political Development -- t5. ASEAN’s Pariah -- t6. Challenging Change -- t7. Blowing Smoke -- t8. Bypassing Regionalism? -- tArguments -- t8. Toward Relative Decency -- t9. Toward Relative Decency -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe region’s most powerful organization, ASEAN, is being challenged to ensure security and encourage democracy while simultaneously reinventing itself as a model of Asian regionalism. Should ASEAN’s leaders defend a member country’s citizens against state predation for the sake of justice - and risk splitting ASEAN itself? Or should regional leaders privilege state security over human security for the sake of order - and risk being known as a dictators’ club? Should ASEAN isolate or tolerate the junta in Myanmar? Is democracy a requisite to security, or is it the other way around? How can democratization become a regional project without fi rst transforming the Association into a "peoplecentered" organization? But how can ASEAN reinvent itself along such lines if its member states are not already democratic? How will its new Charter affect ASEAN’s ability to make these hard choices? How is regionalism being challenged by transnational crime, infectious disease, and other border-jumping threats to human security in Southeast Asia? Why have regional leaders failed to stop the perennial regional "haze" from brush fi res in democratic Indonesia? Does democracy help or hinder nuclear energy security in the region? In this timely book - the second of a three-book series focused on Asian regionalism - ten analysts from six countries address these and other pressing questions that Southeast Asia faces in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDemocracyzSoutheast AsiavCongresses. 0aDemocracy--Southeast Asia--Congresses. 0aNational securityzSoutheast AsiavCongresses. 0aNational security--Southeast Asia--Congresses. 0aRegionalismzSoutheast AsiavCongresses. 0aRegionalism--Southeast Asia--Congresses. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh1 aCaballero-Anthony, Mely, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChalermpalanupap, Termsak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDosch, Jörn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerson, Donald K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerson, Donald K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHlaing, Kyaw Yin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhonta, Erik Martinez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalley, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https: